# GitHub Actions: Structure and Steps

## Workflow structure

- Use descriptive workflow filenames: `build-and-test.yml`, `deploy-prod.yml`.
- Start each workflow with a clear `name` and precise `on` trigger:
  - `push` + branch filters, `pull_request`, `workflow_dispatch`, `schedule` (cron), `workflow_call` (reusable).
- Use `concurrency` for critical workflows or shared resources to prevent race conditions or wasted runs.
- Set workflow-level `permissions` to `contents: read` by default; elevate at job level only when strictly needed (least privilege).
- Prefer reusable workflows (`workflow_call`) for common CI/CD patterns to reduce duplication.

## Jobs

- One job per distinct phase: `build`, `lint`, `test`, `deploy`, `security-scan`.
- Pick runners deliberately: `ubuntu-latest` by default; `windows-latest`, `macos-latest`, or self-hosted only when required.
- Use `needs:` to declare ordering between jobs.
- Use job `outputs:` to pass small values between jobs (artifacts for large payloads).
- Use `if:` conditions for conditional execution (branch gating, event type, previous status). Common helpers: `success()`, `failure()`, `always()`, `cancelled()`.
- Split large workflows into smaller focused jobs that can run in parallel where possible.
- Set `timeout-minutes` on long-running jobs to avoid hung workflows.

### Example — conditional deploy with output passing

```yaml
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    outputs:
      artifact_path: ${{ steps.package_app.outputs.path }}
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@34e114876b0b11c390a56381ad16ebd13914f8d5 # v4.3.1
      - uses: actions/setup-node@3235b876344d2a9aa001b8d1453c930bba69e610 # v3.9.1
        with:
          node-version: 18
      - run: |
          npm ci
          npm run build
      - id: package_app
        run: |
          zip -r dist.zip dist
          echo "path=dist.zip" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"
      - uses: actions/upload-artifact@bbbca2ddaa5d8feaa63e36b76fdaad77386f024f # v7.0.0
        with:
          name: my-app-build
          path: dist.zip

  deploy-staging:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: build
    if: github.ref == 'refs/heads/develop' || github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'
    environment: staging
    steps:
      - uses: actions/download-artifact@3e5f45b2cfb9172054b4087a40e8e0b5a5461e7c # v8.0.1
        with:
          name: my-app-build
      - run: |
          unzip dist.zip
          echo "Deploying to staging..."
```

## Steps and actions

- **Always pin `uses:` to a full commit SHA**, with a version comment for humans:
  - ✅ `uses: actions/checkout@34e114876b0b11c390a56381ad16ebd13914f8d5 # v4.3.1`
  - ❌ `uses: actions/checkout@v4` (mutable; a compromised tag can execute malicious code)
  - ❌ `uses: actions/checkout@main` (also mutable)
- Give every step a `name:` — it shows up in logs and makes debugging easier.
- Combine `run` commands with `&&` for efficiency; use `|` for multi-line scripts and clean up temp files in the same `RUN` block.
- Scope `env:` to the narrowest level (step > job > workflow). Never hardcode secrets.
- Provide all required `with:` inputs explicitly; use `${{ }}` expressions for dynamic values.
- Audit third-party actions before use. Prefer the `actions/` organization and review the source; use Dependabot to keep pinned SHAs current.

## Review checklist (general structure)

- [ ] Workflow `name` is clear, descriptive, and unique.
- [ ] `on` triggers, path filters, and branch filters are correct and minimal.
- [ ] `concurrency` set for workflows that shouldn't overlap.
- [ ] Global `permissions: contents: read`, with overrides only where needed.
- [ ] Reusable workflows used for repeated patterns.
- [ ] Jobs named and represent distinct phases.
- [ ] `needs`, `outputs`, and `if` used correctly.
- [ ] All `uses:` actions pinned to full commit SHA with `# vX.Y.Z` comment.
- [ ] `timeout-minutes` set on long-running jobs.
- [ ] `env` variables scoped appropriately; no hardcoded secrets.
